England":"Carlisle, Cumbria, England, United Kingdom","Lowther, Eden District, Cumbria, England":"Lowther, Cumbria, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"–16 July 1449":"–16 juli 1449","1368–1430":"1368–1430","1395–1455":"1395–1455","–1449":"–1449","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","April 1430":"april 1430","16 July 1449":"16 juli 1449","1430":"1430","1395":"1395","1449":"1449","Cumbria, England":"Cumbria, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lowther, Westmorland, England":"Lowther, Westmorland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Carlisle, City of Carlisle, Cumbria, England":"Carlisle, Cumbria, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lowther, Eden District, Cumbria, England":"Lowther, Cumbria, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–16 July 1449":"–16 July 1449","1368–1430":"1368–1430","1395–1455":"1395–1455","–1449":"–1449","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","April 1430":"April 1430","16 July 1449":"16 July 1449","1430":"1430","1395":"1395","1449":"1449","Cumbria, England":"Cumbria, England, United Kingdom","Lowther, Westmorland, England":"Lowther, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Carlisle, City of Carlisle, Cumbria, England":"Carlisle, Cumbria, England, United Kingdom","Lowther, Eden District, Cumbria, England":"Lowther, Cumbria, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lowther","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Cumbria, so called from the river on which it stands. The placename is of obscure etymology, perhaps of ancient Welsh origin (compare   Lauder  ), or from Old Norse <i>lauthr</i> ‘froth, foam’ + <i>á</i> ‘river’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lawther","meanings":["Scottish, northern Irish, and northern English: variant of   Lowther   and   Lauder  ."]},{"name":"Lauder","meanings":["Scottish (Borders): habitational name from Lauder in Berwickshire, originally a name for the river Leader (itself from British <i>lou-</i> + <i>dubro-</i> ‘cleansing river’). Compare   Lauderdale  ."]},{"name":"Lattea","meanings":["Altered form of English   Lowther  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Lowther was born in England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Robert Lowther. She died on 16 July 1449, in Cumbria, England, United Kingdom, and was buried in Carlisle, Cumbria, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"–16 July 1449":"–16. juuli 1449","1368–1430":"1368–1430","1395–1455":"1395–1455","–1449":"–1449","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","April 1430":"aprill 1430","16 July 1449":"16. juuli 1449","1430":"1430","1395":"1395","1449":"1449","Cumbria, England":"Cumbria, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lowther, Westmorland, England":"Lowther, Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Carlisle, City of Carlisle, Cumbria, England":"Carlisle, Cumbria, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lowther, Eden District, Cumbria, England":"Lowther, Cumbria, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–16 July 1449":"–16. heinäkuuta 1449","1368–1430":"1368–1430","1395–1455":"1395–1455","–1449":"–1449","1368":"1368","1455":"1455","April 1430":"huhtikuu 1430","16 July 1449":"16. heinäkuuta 1449","1430":"1430","1395":"1395","1449":"1449","Cumbria, England":"Cumbria, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lowther, Westmorland, England":"Lowther, Westmorland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Carlisle, City of Carlisle, Cumbria, England":"Carlisle, Cumbria, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lowther, Eden District, Cumbria, England":"Lowther, Cumbria, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–16 July 1449":"–16 juillet 14